Observations:

Dataset Size: The training set contains 20,000 observations, each with 41 columns (40 predictors and 1 target variable). The test set includes 5,000 observations, also with 41 columns.

Data Types: Both datasets primarily consist of numerical features (float64), with the target variable being an integer (int64).

Missing Values: In the training set, two variables (V1 and V2) have 18 missing values each. In the test set, V1 has 5 missing values, and V2 has 6 missing values. No missing values are present in the target variable of both datasets.

Data Integrity: There are no duplicate rows in either the training or the test dataset, indicating good data integrity.

Class Imbalance: Bot training and testing target variables have imbalanced distribution of the target variables classes where: About 94.4% of the observations belong to the negative class (0), which represents "Non-failure" cases. About 5% of the observations belong to the positive class (1), representing "Failure" cases.

Model Building

In [139]:
#creating a funcion for metrics evaluation for predicted values
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score,accuracy_score,precision_score,recall_score,confusion_matrix,classification_report
def metrics_evaluation(model,predictors,target):
    y_pred=model.predict(predictors)
    acc=accuracy_score(target,y_pred)
    rec=recall_score(target,y_pred)
    f1=f1_score(target,y_pred)
    precision=precision_score(target,y_pred),
    metrics_df=pd.DataFrame({'Accuarcy': acc,'Recall': rec,'Precision ' : precision,'F1 score' :f1},index=[0])
    return metrics_df
In [168]:
def confusion_mat(model,predictors,target):
    y_pred=model.predict(predictors)
    cm=confusion_matrix(target,y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.heatmap(cm,annot=labels,fmt="")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted values")
    plt.ylabel("True values")
    plt.show()
Defining scorer for cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning .The goal here is to reduce the mainataince cost and to reduce the number of repairs, recall is choose to minimize the false negatives .So, use Recall as a scorer

models=[]
models.append(('Decision Tree',DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Random Forest',RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Logistic Regression',LogisticRegression(random_state=42,max_iter=1000)))
models.append(('Bagging classifier',BaggingClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Adaboost',AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Gradient Boosting',GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42)))

results_original=[]
names=[]

print("The cross validation recall scores:\n")
kfold=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5,shuffle=True, random_state=42)
for name,model in models:
    res=cross_val_score(model,X_train,y_train, scoring=scorer, cv=kfold)
    results_original.append(res)
    names.append(name)
    print(name,":",res.mean())
print("recall score on validation set")
for name,model in models:
    model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    y_val_pred=model.predict(X_val)
    score=recall_score(y_val,y_val_pred)
    print(name,":",score)

    model.fit(X_train_over,y_train_over)
    y_val_pred=model.predict(X_val)

    print(name,":",score)

#model building on oversampled data
models=[]
models.append(('Decision Tree',DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Random Forest',RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Logistic Regression',LogisticRegression(random_state=42,max_iter=1000)))
models.append(('Bagging classifier',BaggingClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Adaboost',AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Gradient Boosting',GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42)))

results_under_sampled=[]
names=[]

print("The cross validation recall scores:\n")
kfold=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5,shuffle=True, random_state=42)
for name,model in models:
    res=cross_val_score(model,X_train_un,y_train_un, scoring=scorer, cv=kfold)
    results_under_sampled.append(res)
    names.append(name)
    print(name,":",res.mean())
print("\nrecall score on validation set\n")
for name,model in models:
    model.fit(X_train_un,y_train_un)
    y_val_pred=model.predict(X_val)
    score=recall_score(y_val,y_val_pred)
    print(name,":",score)

    "n_estimators": [100, 150, 200],
    "learning_rate": [0.2, 0.05],
    "estimator": [DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=1, random_state=1),
                       DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, random_state=1),
                       DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, random_state=1), ] }
